JAVA COLLECTION FRAMEWORK
│
├── 1. LIST  (Ordered, Allows duplicates)
│     │
│     ├── ArrayList
│     │     • Dynamic array
│     │     • Fast access (get/set)
│     │     • Slow insertion in middle
│     │     • Example: students list
│     │
│     └── LinkedList
│           • Doubly linked list
│           • Fast insertion/deletion
│           • Good for queue/stack
│           • Example: tasks list
│
├── 2. SET  (No duplicates)
│     │
│     ├── HashSet
│     │     • No duplicates
│     │     • Not sorted
│     │     • Fast search (Hash)
│     │     • Example: unique values
│     │
│     └── TreeSet
│           • Sorted set
│           • No duplicates
│           • Useful for ranking
│           • Example: sorted numbers
│
├── 3. MAP  (Key–Value Pair)
│     │
│     └── HashMap
│           • Stores data as key=value
│           • Fast lookup
│           • Keys must be unique
│           • Example: ID → Name
│
├── 4. QUEUE  (FIFO)
│     │
│     └── LinkedList / PriorityQueue
│           • add() → insert
│           • poll() → remove first
│           • Example: task processing
│
├── 5. STACK  (LIFO)
│     │
│     └── Stack
│           • push() → add on top
│           • pop() → remove top
│           • Example: Undo operation
│
└── 6. Collections Utility Class
       • Collections.sort() → sort
       • Collections.reverse() → reverse
       • Collections.max() / min()
       • Helps with operations on lists
       
       
       
       
SUPER SIMPLE SUMMARY (One-Liner Memory)

ArrayList  → Fast access

LinkedList → Fast insertion

HashSet    → Unique only

TreeSet    → Unique + Sorted

HashMap    → Key–Value

Queue      → First In First Out (FIFO)

Stack      → Last In First Out (LIFO)

Collections class → sort, reverse, max, min
